const List<String> celebrateDescription = [
  "The Rath Yatra in Puri sees the annual procession of Lord Jagannatha, Lord Balabhadra, and Goddess Subhadra from Srimandira to Gundicha Temple, marking one of Odisha's grandest festivals. The elaborate chariots, led by the 45-ft-high Nandighosa for Lord Jagannatha, adorned with floral decorations, carry the deities amidst the sounds of trumpets and cymbals, drawing thousands of devotees. After a ceremonial cleaning by the Gajapati king, the chariots move along the grand avenue to Gundicha Temple, where the deities reside for a week before returning in the Bahuda Yatra.",
  "Celebrate International Yoga Day by embarking on a transformative journey through India's enchanting destinations. Experience the profound power of yoga while immersing yourself in the sacred energy of places like Rishikesh and Kerala's tranquil ashrams. Explore ancient wisdom and connect with your inner self amidst the serene beauty of these sacred locations.",
  "The festival dedicated to St. John the Baptist in Goa is a vibrant celebration where locals don colorful kopels made of fruits, flowers, and vegetables and dance joyously. With origins dating back 175 years, it commemorates the biblical narrative of St. John's birth and his role in baptizing Jesus in the River Jordan, as described in the Bible. Participants also symbolically mark baptism by jumping into water bodies, echoing the spiritual significance of the event.",
  "The Hemis Festival, held annually in the Hemis Monastery, celebrates the birth anniversary of Guru Padmasambhava over two days during the Tse-Chu lunar month. Locals adorn traditional attire and gather in the monastery's courtyard to witness lamas performing cham dances accompanied by drums, cymbals, and horns, with some presenting plays for the audience's delight. The festival's charm lies in the vibrant costumes of the lamas, characterized by intricate masks, long gowns, and elaborate headgear, each mask carrying its unique symbolic significance, adding to the enchantment of the event.",
  "Eid-ul-Zuha, also known as Bakr-Id, is a significant Muslim festival marked by special prayers, greetings, and the exchange of gifts. It commemorates the story of Ibrahim's willingness to sacrifice his son Ismail, with the tradition of sacrificing a goat or sheep symbolizing this act of obedience to Allah's command. According to Islamic tradition, Muslims owning property of a certain value are expected to perform this sacrifice during the three-day festival, with the meat distributed among the less fortunate as a gesture of charity and goodwill.",
  "The Champakulam Boat Race, one of Kerala's oldest and most renowned events, celebrates the state's cultural heritage with thrilling snake boat races on the River Pampa. Held on the auspicious day of 'moolam' in the Malayalam month of Midhunam, the festival commemorates the deity's return to Ambalappuzha Sree Krishna Temple. The sight of frenzied rowers propelling massive boats in perfect synchrony, accompanied by local folk music, creates a spectacular spectacle reminiscent of a legendary event where thousands of vibrant boats escorted the idol of Sri Krishna to the temple.",
];


